Steve Gardner wrote:
>
>I think this is fine. The most natural way to think of Voting Periods is
>as an attribute of Proposals which is fixed at the time they are
>distributed.

"Most natural" is highly subjective.  Is there anything in the Rules
to support such an interpretation?  It seems to me that that is
contrary to the Rule that a Rule Change resulting from a Proposal
takes effect when the Proposal results are distributed, and of
Rule 101--that Rules, at any time, are obeyed in the form in which
they are then in effect.  If we say the VPs of these Proposals
are still ten days, aren't we obeying a former form of the Rule
rather than the current form?

>(One might argue that the application need not be retroactive: we might
>think of the effect of the amendment as changing, in the present, the
>value of the Proposals' attribute "length-of-VP". But at least in this
>case, that argument won't quite work, since the effect will be to make
>it the case, in the present, that the VPs ended a few days ago - and
>that is a change in the past.)

I've argued against such an interpretation before.  Just becasue we are
setting a new designation of a time in the past does not mean that the change
of designation actually takes place in the past.  Analogy: a Rule stating,
"July 4 1776 is recognized as the birthday of the United States" is not
retroactive simply because it changes the designation of a date in the
past.  The designation becomes effective at the time the
Rule is enacted, not on July 4 1776, and is not retroactive simply
because it refers to a date in the past.

Chuck

