>
>I've argued against such an interpretation before.  Just becasue we are
>setting a new designation of a time in the past does not mean that the change
>of designation actually takes place in the past.  Analogy: a Rule stating,
>"July 4 1776 is recognized as the birthday of the United States" is not
>retroactive simply because it changes the designation of a date in the
>past.  The designation becomes effective at the time the
>Rule is enacted, not on July 4 1776, and is not retroactive simply
>because it refers to a date in the past.

I think that is a poor analogy. What is involved here is more than just
reference to a date in the past. Here we are trying to determine whether
or not specific events (such as the conclusions of Voting Periods, and
the legal castings of votes) did or did not take place in the past. If
we now say that the VPs of Proposals 3810-3812 concluded on Monday, then
votes cast after that time but before the passage of P3809 which were
legally cast at the time they were cast are having their legal statuses
changed retrospectively.

To put it another way: how can it be true on Monday afternoon that the
VPs did not conclude on Monday morning, but false on Tuesday morning
that they did not conclude on Monday morning, without a retrospective
change?

